Predicting Bike rentals

Joel Casillas, Ravinder Singh, and Ryan LeBon

May 8, 2018

Introduction

This dataset contains the hourly and daily count of rental bikes between years 2011 and 2012 in Capital bikeshare system with the corresponding weather and seasonal information. The data set is fairly new and small in the sense that it has only has 2 years of data. So any predictions created must be taken lighlty. The data set has 731 rows, and 16 columns total.

Capital Bikeshare is metro DCs bikeshare service, with 4,300 bikes and 500 stations across 5 jurisdictions: Washington, DC.; Arlington, VA; Alexandria, VA; Montgomery, MD and Fairfax County, VA. Designed for quick trips with convenience in mind, its a fun and affordable way to get around.

Hypothesis: Our goal for this project is to predict the bicycle rentals.

Data Cleaning & Pre-Processing

There were two types of data sets from the start. A day dataset and an hour dataset. The data was clean from the start, their were no Nas or missing values in it. We removed a few columns from the dataset, we removed instance,casual,registered, and dteday. These columns were removed because they either negatively affected the models and or they were redundant columns made up of other columns data.

dat=read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ryanbbq/datascience_final/master/day.csv")
hour=read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Ryanbbq/datascience_final/master/hour.csv")

We will be exploring the data to see whether this data is consists of supervised or unspervised learning. We will also learn about the features and how they correlate and interact with each other.

In this model, we have used a Regression Tree. We also decided to use the features such as temperature , windspeed and humidity. Also, temp and atemp features in this dataset are normalized in celsius. We also splitted 75% of the data into training dataset and 25% into test dataset.

Linear Regression Model

To choose the best feaures for the model, I decided to use the caret library. I used the function varImp, which means variable importance. I first made a fitted linear model using all the features and from there I ran the function varImp. From there I decided to create a new fitted mdodel with all the features except the one variable with the least importance. We also converted the features season,month,temparture and weather into factors to get better model accuracy.

oldfit=lm(cnt~.,data = dat)
varImp(oldfit)
##              Overall
## season      9.309748
## yr         31.306209
## mnth        2.282301
## holiday     2.581531
## weekday     4.237213
## workingday  1.671455
## weathersit  7.796851
## temp        1.445436
## atemp       2.248207
## hum         3.244832
## windspeed   5.605293
fit = lm(cnt~season+mnth+holiday+weekday+weathersit+windspeed+hum+atemp+as.factor(temp)+
           as.factor(yr),data = dat) 
predicted = predict(fit, tr_dat)
actual= tr_dat$cnt
plot_predict_actual(predicted,actual,2000,title = "Predictions from Training Data")

This model is fitted using the best features to predict rentals of bikes in a day for the next year. This shows us that the model did pretty well on the training data, but thats expected, the real test is running it on test data.

predicted3 = predict(fit, te_dat)
actual3= te_dat$cnt
plot_predict_actual(predicted3,actual3,2000,title = "Predictions from Test Data")

Here we ran our fitted model on our test data and as you can see, it did a decent job of predicting bike rentals in a day. There is alot of residual on some parts but for the most part, the dots are close to the fitted line.

predicted = predict(fit, te_dat)
errors = te_dat$cnt - predicted
rmse = sqrt(mean(errors^2))
paste0("The RMSE is ",rmse)
## [1] "The RMSE is 355.482076608152"

Conclusion

Based on our hypothesis we found out the that the top 3 features were seasons, temperature, and humidity which lead to a user renting out a bicycle. Linear regression performed well on this particular dataset compared to decision tree regression. Linear regression works really nicely when the data has a linear shape. In case the dataset didnt have linear shape then linear regression would not capture the non-linear features. Therefore, decision tree regression could have performed betters than linear regression.
